{"data":{"mdx":{"html":"<div><p>I recently finished my first handwired Atreus keyboard, an ortholinear keyboard with 42 keys. I&#x27;m really happy with how it turned out and I&#x27;m just documenting how it went for me, as well as some reference for my future builds. I&#x27;m proud of how it turned out and excited to do another soon! </p><h3>Final product</h3><p><a class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\" href=\"/static/df40b4c89a33be5d79a1789fd9be981b/5f4b4/final.jpg\" style=\"display:block\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\" style=\"position:relative;display:block;max-width:590px;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto\"><span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\" style=\"padding-bottom:49.34065934065934%;position:relative;bottom:0px;left:0px;background-size:cover;display:block\"></span><img class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\" style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0px;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0px;left:0px;box-shadow:inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white\" alt=\"final\" title=\"\" src=\"/static/df40b4c89a33be5d79a1789fd9be981b/a6d7d/final.jpg\" srcSet=\"/static/df40b4c89a33be5d79a1789fd9be981b/51d5b/final.jpg 148w,\n/static/df40b4c89a33be5d79a1789fd9be981b/9118c/final.jpg 295w,\n/static/df40b4c89a33be5d79a1789fd9be981b/a6d7d/final.jpg 590w,\n/static/df40b4c89a33be5d79a1789fd9be981b/ea746/final.jpg 885w,\n/static/df40b4c89a33be5d79a1789fd9be981b/9b641/final.jpg 1180w,\n/static/df40b4c89a33be5d79a1789fd9be981b/444d5/final.jpg 1770w,\n/static/df40b4c89a33be5d79a1789fd9be981b/5f4b4/final.jpg 2730w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"/></span></a></p><p>This is a cross-section of both top and bottom of the keyboard. The bottom is clear acrylic so I can show off my handiwork! </p><p>I researched the hell out of this thing before starting, because I practically knew nothing about the circuitry of how a keyboard matrix worked. The biggest hurdle was knowing the software well enough to enable the hardware. I was lucky in that the <a href=\"https://atreus.technomancy.us/assembly-hand-wired.pdf\">Atreus hand wire guide</a> is pretty comprehensive, as well as relying on great resources like this <a href=\"https://imgur.com/a/qcgdF\">&quot;Modern handwiring guide&quot;</a>. I already knew a fair amount about pro micros from previous builds (I&#x27;ve built 4 other keyboards but with PCBs) so that gave me lots of information about its limitations and where stuff goes; as well as with experience with <a href=\"https://github.com/qmk/qmk_firmware\">QMK</a>. There are plenty of awesome and active people on the QMK Gitter if you get stuck with the firmware. I also had plenty of help from the great people in the <a href=\"https://discord.gg/tjjT8J\">UTMK discord</a> (which welcomes anyone really) regarding the hardware aspect of my build.</p><h3>Build in review</h3><p><a class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\" href=\"/static/b2b4b59c5be9274ef2da82cde8ae4f5f/f5b1e/1.jpg\" style=\"display:block\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\" style=\"position:relative;display:block;max-width:590px;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto\"><span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\" style=\"padding-bottom:56.25%;position:relative;bottom:0px;left:0px;background-size:cover;display:block\"></span><img class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\" style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0px;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0px;left:0px;box-shadow:inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white\" alt=\"1\" title=\"\" src=\"/static/b2b4b59c5be9274ef2da82cde8ae4f5f/a6d7d/1.jpg\" srcSet=\"/static/b2b4b59c5be9274ef2da82cde8ae4f5f/51d5b/1.jpg 148w,\n/static/b2b4b59c5be9274ef2da82cde8ae4f5f/9118c/1.jpg 295w,\n/static/b2b4b59c5be9274ef2da82cde8ae4f5f/a6d7d/1.jpg 590w,\n/static/b2b4b59c5be9274ef2da82cde8ae4f5f/ea746/1.jpg 885w,\n/static/b2b4b59c5be9274ef2da82cde8ae4f5f/9b641/1.jpg 1180w,\n/static/b2b4b59c5be9274ef2da82cde8ae4f5f/444d5/1.jpg 1770w,\n/static/b2b4b59c5be9274ef2da82cde8ae4f5f/f5b1e/1.jpg 2784w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"/></span></a></p><p>The case is laser cut from Â¼&quot; plywood. A friend sold it to me after finding that it wouldn&#x27;t work for his Atreus PCB. Here I&#x27;m putting in the switches; the black ones are Gateron Clears, the whites are Kalih Pro Purples.</p><p><a class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\" href=\"/static/83d18f005cf9ab2da4ab15ace66611cf/f5b1e/2.jpg\" style=\"display:block\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\" style=\"position:relative;display:block;max-width:590px;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto\"><span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\" style=\"padding-bottom:75%;position:relative;bottom:0px;left:0px;background-size:cover;display:block\"></span><img class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\" style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0px;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0px;left:0px;box-shadow:inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white\" alt=\"2\" title=\"\" src=\"/static/83d18f005cf9ab2da4ab15ace66611cf/a6d7d/2.jpg\" srcSet=\"/static/83d18f005cf9ab2da4ab15ace66611cf/51d5b/2.jpg 148w,\n/static/83d18f005cf9ab2da4ab15ace66611cf/9118c/2.jpg 295w,\n/static/83d18f005cf9ab2da4ab15ace66611cf/a6d7d/2.jpg 590w,\n/static/83d18f005cf9ab2da4ab15ace66611cf/ea746/2.jpg 885w,\n/static/83d18f005cf9ab2da4ab15ace66611cf/9b641/2.jpg 1180w,\n/static/83d18f005cf9ab2da4ab15ace66611cf/444d5/2.jpg 1770w,\n/static/83d18f005cf9ab2da4ab15ace66611cf/f5b1e/2.jpg 2784w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"/></span></a></p><p>Hot glued the switches in. If I could go back, I would have added the keycaps to the switches so that I could rotate them to better rotate/align them with one another before gluing them down. Lesson learned.</p><p><a class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\" href=\"/static/0c930e34829e7d07e06fca2cfdc856d5/f5b1e/3.jpg\" style=\"display:block\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\" style=\"position:relative;display:block;max-width:590px;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto\"><span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\" style=\"padding-bottom:56.25%;position:relative;bottom:0px;left:0px;background-size:cover;display:block\"></span><img class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\" style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0px;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0px;left:0px;box-shadow:inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white\" alt=\"3\" title=\"\" src=\"/static/0c930e34829e7d07e06fca2cfdc856d5/a6d7d/3.jpg\" srcSet=\"/static/0c930e34829e7d07e06fca2cfdc856d5/51d5b/3.jpg 148w,\n/static/0c930e34829e7d07e06fca2cfdc856d5/9118c/3.jpg 295w,\n/static/0c930e34829e7d07e06fca2cfdc856d5/a6d7d/3.jpg 590w,\n/static/0c930e34829e7d07e06fca2cfdc856d5/ea746/3.jpg 885w,\n/static/0c930e34829e7d07e06fca2cfdc856d5/9b641/3.jpg 1180w,\n/static/0c930e34829e7d07e06fca2cfdc856d5/444d5/3.jpg 1770w,\n/static/0c930e34829e7d07e06fca2cfdc856d5/f5b1e/3.jpg 2784w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"/></span></a></p><p>Diodes all added. Many guides recommend using loops so I did. This technique works <em>really</em> well. In some other builds, the downward facing leg of the diode is simply bent and soldered to the adjacent diode; I instead connected them to a row wire (blue) which ends up looking much more polished in my opinion.</p><p><a class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\" href=\"/static/32b32b3b4b39d386f6de4c7b0ccb82ac/f5b1e/4.jpg\" style=\"display:block\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\" style=\"position:relative;display:block;max-width:590px;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto\"><span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\" style=\"padding-bottom:75%;position:relative;bottom:0px;left:0px;background-size:cover;display:block\"></span><img class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\" style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0px;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0px;left:0px;box-shadow:inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white\" alt=\"4\" title=\"\" src=\"/static/32b32b3b4b39d386f6de4c7b0ccb82ac/a6d7d/4.jpg\" srcSet=\"/static/32b32b3b4b39d386f6de4c7b0ccb82ac/51d5b/4.jpg 148w,\n/static/32b32b3b4b39d386f6de4c7b0ccb82ac/9118c/4.jpg 295w,\n/static/32b32b3b4b39d386f6de4c7b0ccb82ac/a6d7d/4.jpg 590w,\n/static/32b32b3b4b39d386f6de4c7b0ccb82ac/ea746/4.jpg 885w,\n/static/32b32b3b4b39d386f6de4c7b0ccb82ac/9b641/4.jpg 1180w,\n/static/32b32b3b4b39d386f6de4c7b0ccb82ac/444d5/4.jpg 1770w,\n/static/32b32b3b4b39d386f6de4c7b0ccb82ac/f5b1e/4.jpg 2784w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"/></span></a></p><p>Close up of diodes. If you look closely, the diode on the white switch is reversed... didn&#x27;t find this error until after everything else was all put together.</p><p><a class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\" href=\"/static/92810f88675d2f7927d6887f90681ee2/6f4e1/5.jpg\" style=\"display:block\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\" style=\"position:relative;display:block;max-width:590px;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto\"><span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\" style=\"padding-bottom:177.77777777777777%;position:relative;bottom:0px;left:0px;background-size:cover;display:block\"></span><img class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\" style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0px;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0px;left:0px;box-shadow:inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white\" alt=\"5\" title=\"\" src=\"/static/92810f88675d2f7927d6887f90681ee2/a6d7d/5.jpg\" srcSet=\"/static/92810f88675d2f7927d6887f90681ee2/51d5b/5.jpg 148w,\n/static/92810f88675d2f7927d6887f90681ee2/9118c/5.jpg 295w,\n/static/92810f88675d2f7927d6887f90681ee2/a6d7d/5.jpg 590w,\n/static/92810f88675d2f7927d6887f90681ee2/ea746/5.jpg 885w,\n/static/92810f88675d2f7927d6887f90681ee2/9b641/5.jpg 1180w,\n/static/92810f88675d2f7927d6887f90681ee2/6f4e1/5.jpg 1566w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"/></span></a></p><p>Single row wire just before soldering.</p><p><a class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\" href=\"/static/91e8aa1f4286813c9a801a794c7d163b/f5b1e/6.jpg\" style=\"display:block\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\" style=\"position:relative;display:block;max-width:590px;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto\"><span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\" style=\"padding-bottom:56.25%;position:relative;bottom:0px;left:0px;background-size:cover;display:block\"></span><img class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\" style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0px;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0px;left:0px;box-shadow:inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white\" alt=\"6\" title=\"\" src=\"/static/91e8aa1f4286813c9a801a794c7d163b/a6d7d/6.jpg\" srcSet=\"/static/91e8aa1f4286813c9a801a794c7d163b/51d5b/6.jpg 148w,\n/static/91e8aa1f4286813c9a801a794c7d163b/9118c/6.jpg 295w,\n/static/91e8aa1f4286813c9a801a794c7d163b/a6d7d/6.jpg 590w,\n/static/91e8aa1f4286813c9a801a794c7d163b/ea746/6.jpg 885w,\n/static/91e8aa1f4286813c9a801a794c7d163b/9b641/6.jpg 1180w,\n/static/91e8aa1f4286813c9a801a794c7d163b/444d5/6.jpg 1770w,\n/static/91e8aa1f4286813c9a801a794c7d163b/f5b1e/6.jpg 2784w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"/></span></a></p><p>Row wires connected. Use solid core wire and things will be <em>much</em> easier for you. I used stranded wire from an ethernet cable, and had to redo them a couple of times since I cut through too many strands while trying to remove the insulation. I also developed my own technique with a v-notch wire stripper after a while, to be able to remove the insulation quickly without the inner strands. Just use solid core.</p><p><a class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\" href=\"/static/bcb026f3373c08055f66173426bdb5d1/6f4e1/7.jpg\" style=\"display:block\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\" style=\"position:relative;display:block;max-width:590px;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto\"><span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\" style=\"padding-bottom:177.77777777777777%;position:relative;bottom:0px;left:0px;background-size:cover;display:block\"></span><img class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\" style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0px;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0px;left:0px;box-shadow:inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white\" alt=\"7\" title=\"\" src=\"/static/bcb026f3373c08055f66173426bdb5d1/a6d7d/7.jpg\" srcSet=\"/static/bcb026f3373c08055f66173426bdb5d1/51d5b/7.jpg 148w,\n/static/bcb026f3373c08055f66173426bdb5d1/9118c/7.jpg 295w,\n/static/bcb026f3373c08055f66173426bdb5d1/a6d7d/7.jpg 590w,\n/static/bcb026f3373c08055f66173426bdb5d1/ea746/7.jpg 885w,\n/static/bcb026f3373c08055f66173426bdb5d1/9b641/7.jpg 1180w,\n/static/bcb026f3373c08055f66173426bdb5d1/6f4e1/7.jpg 1566w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"/></span></a></p><p>Next came the column wires. These were easier since they are shorter.</p><p><a class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\" href=\"/static/c4f01b4a5461fe09861d5c0627ac7521/f5b1e/8.jpg\" style=\"display:block\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\" style=\"position:relative;display:block;max-width:590px;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto\"><span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\" style=\"padding-bottom:56.25%;position:relative;bottom:0px;left:0px;background-size:cover;display:block\"></span><img class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\" style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0px;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0px;left:0px;box-shadow:inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white\" alt=\"8\" title=\"\" src=\"/static/c4f01b4a5461fe09861d5c0627ac7521/a6d7d/8.jpg\" srcSet=\"/static/c4f01b4a5461fe09861d5c0627ac7521/51d5b/8.jpg 148w,\n/static/c4f01b4a5461fe09861d5c0627ac7521/9118c/8.jpg 295w,\n/static/c4f01b4a5461fe09861d5c0627ac7521/a6d7d/8.jpg 590w,\n/static/c4f01b4a5461fe09861d5c0627ac7521/ea746/8.jpg 885w,\n/static/c4f01b4a5461fe09861d5c0627ac7521/9b641/8.jpg 1180w,\n/static/c4f01b4a5461fe09861d5c0627ac7521/444d5/8.jpg 1770w,\n/static/c4f01b4a5461fe09861d5c0627ac7521/f5b1e/8.jpg 2784w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"/></span></a></p><p>Close up of column wires. You can&#x27;t tell from this picture, but the top-rightmost switch had a short. The wires were a little too taught so when I soldered the column wire the insulation between the two melted together and the wire cores touched. Just had to pull them away from each other and that was it. I ended up having 3 shorts total, all because of the same thing.</p><p><a class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\" href=\"/static/feed0f5628f207f0f4b397b22ee3faa2/f5b1e/9.jpg\" style=\"display:block\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\" style=\"position:relative;display:block;max-width:590px;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto\"><span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\" style=\"padding-bottom:56.25%;position:relative;bottom:0px;left:0px;background-size:cover;display:block\"></span><img class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\" style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0px;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0px;left:0px;box-shadow:inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white\" alt=\"9\" title=\"\" src=\"/static/feed0f5628f207f0f4b397b22ee3faa2/a6d7d/9.jpg\" srcSet=\"/static/feed0f5628f207f0f4b397b22ee3faa2/51d5b/9.jpg 148w,\n/static/feed0f5628f207f0f4b397b22ee3faa2/9118c/9.jpg 295w,\n/static/feed0f5628f207f0f4b397b22ee3faa2/a6d7d/9.jpg 590w,\n/static/feed0f5628f207f0f4b397b22ee3faa2/ea746/9.jpg 885w,\n/static/feed0f5628f207f0f4b397b22ee3faa2/9b641/9.jpg 1180w,\n/static/feed0f5628f207f0f4b397b22ee3faa2/444d5/9.jpg 1770w,\n/static/feed0f5628f207f0f4b397b22ee3faa2/f5b1e/9.jpg 2784w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"/></span></a></p><p>Final product! I had tried to &quot;bend&quot; the green row wires to make it look nicer and let me organize them together better but... didn&#x27;t achieve the intended effect. Still like the way it turned out, especially for a first time build! Here you can see the speaker I&#x27;ve added too. This keyboard can make noise! Here&#x27;s a video of it playing the Imperial March on startup: <a href=\"https://youtu.be/XQPiW4ZtcOY\">https://youtu.be/XQPiW4ZtcOY</a></p><p>I ended up setting it to play the Zelda Treasure chime on startup instead.</p><p>TL;DR of things I learned while attempting to add this audio feature: </p><ul><li>Pin C6 or B5 has to be unused and can&#x27;t be shared with any keys</li><li>Setting B5 in the firmware never seemed to work for me, so I freed up C6 instead, soldered the speaker to that, and everything was good </li><li>Enabling audio ends up taking a fair chunk of memory; you may need to disable other QMK features or you might brick the controller (which I believe I actually did on another keyboard)</li><li>The novelty factor was worth it. My kid loves playing with it in music mode, and my coworkers have fun with it too.</li></ul><p>My custom layout can be found on my <a href=\"https://github.com/filoxo/keyboard-layouts\">Keyboard Layouts repo</a>. </p><p><a class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\" href=\"/static/b0cb4d40cf9c8c31b2038f112e0bb856/f5b1e/10.jpg\" style=\"display:block\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\" style=\"position:relative;display:block;max-width:590px;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto\"><span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\" style=\"padding-bottom:56.25%;position:relative;bottom:0px;left:0px;background-size:cover;display:block\"></span><img class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\" style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0px;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0px;left:0px;box-shadow:inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white\" alt=\"10\" title=\"\" src=\"/static/b0cb4d40cf9c8c31b2038f112e0bb856/a6d7d/10.jpg\" srcSet=\"/static/b0cb4d40cf9c8c31b2038f112e0bb856/51d5b/10.jpg 148w,\n/static/b0cb4d40cf9c8c31b2038f112e0bb856/9118c/10.jpg 295w,\n/static/b0cb4d40cf9c8c31b2038f112e0bb856/a6d7d/10.jpg 590w,\n/static/b0cb4d40cf9c8c31b2038f112e0bb856/ea746/10.jpg 885w,\n/static/b0cb4d40cf9c8c31b2038f112e0bb856/9b641/10.jpg 1180w,\n/static/b0cb4d40cf9c8c31b2038f112e0bb856/444d5/10.jpg 1770w,\n/static/b0cb4d40cf9c8c31b2038f112e0bb856/f5b1e/10.jpg 2784w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"/></span></a></p><p>Top view of the keyboard with keycaps. The next steps will probably disassemble to to stain/treat the wood before using heavily, as well as add a strip of LEDs for some underglow.</p></div>","frontmatter":{"title":"Building my first handwired keyboard","date":"Feb 12, 2018","tags":["keyboards"]}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/2018-02-12-building-my-first-handwired-keyboard/"}}